Module root that documents and re-exports the `bwrap` argv-building subsystem for the safety cage; contains no logic itself beyond `mod`/`pub use` declarations. Actual argv construction lives in `build.rs` (`build_bwrap_args`) and config types/constants live in `config.rs` (`BwrapConfig` plus path constants `API_SOCK_NAME`, `CAGE_BIN`, `CAGE_CLAUDE_CONFIG`, `CAGE_CLAUDE_CRED`, `CAGE_LOCAL_CLAUDE`, `CAGE_RULES_PATH`, `CAGE_RUN_DIR`).

The doc comment is the load-bearing spec for the whole subsystem's mount layout — anyone editing `build.rs` or `config.rs` must keep the actual bind-mount set in sync with what's described here: target project RW-bound at its real host path (not a fixed alias — this is ADR-046, required so a build compiled inside the cage sees the identical path outside it), secret files masked with empty-file RO binds, toolchain dirs RO-bound at identical host paths, `/cage/bin` as a tmpfs holding RO-bound host CTX tools plus `claude`, `/opt/cage/rules.md` RO-bound, and `/run/ctx` RO-bound as the run dir containing the API proxy socket — the cage's only egress path, since the cage has no network access otherwise.

This module and its children (`build.rs`, `config.rs`) are pure: no I/O, no filesystem access, no subprocess execution. They only transform an already-resolved `BwrapConfig` into a `Vec<OsString>`. The caller (in the lifecycle module elsewhere in the crate) is responsible for resolving the config from CLI flags and environment, then actually invoking `Command::new("bwrap").args(...)` with the output of `build_bwrap_args`.